// Canonical Sutra declarations for the transcendental-function
// family (log / sqrt / exp / trig / pow). All seven are wired to
// real implementations as of 2026-04-29; both numpy and pytorch
// backends emit substrate-pure runtime methods.
//
// **Architecture:**
//   - cos / sin: eigenrotation primitive — R(theta) applied to (1, 0)
//     yields (cos theta, sin theta) directly. This is the user's
//     "they're eigenrotations" understanding from the design chat.
//   - exp(z) for complex z = re + i*im: realExp(re) via degree-25
//     Taylor + 5-pass squaring range reduction (no libm, no floor),
//     composed with the cos/sin eigenrotation of im.
//   - log(z) = ln|z| + i*atan2(im, re). ln via frexp range reduction
//     (IEEE 754 exponent extraction, a substrate primitive — bit
//     manipulation, NOT a transcendental) plus artanh series on the
//     mantissa in [0.5, 1). atan2 via Gregory series + quadrant
//     decomposition.
//   - sqrt = exp(0.5 * log).
//   - pow(x, y) = exp(y * log(x)).
//   - tan = sin / cos.
//
// **Bound-table-via-binding** (the originally-sketched design from
// chats/implementing-transcendental-functions.md) is used only for
// cos/sin, where the eigenrotation gives FP-precise results. For
// non-periodic functions (exp, ln) the bound-table architecture has
// a fundamental capacity limit (the 2-scalar bundle can only encode
// one DFT coefficient of the function). See
// planning/findings/2026-04-29-bound-table-capacity-limit.md.


// ==========================================================================
// Section 1 — what each function will compile to (design notes)
// ==========================================================================
//
// log(x), x ∈ [a, b], a > 0
//   Chebyshev polynomial on the bounded domain. The compiler reads
//   `[math].approximation_precision` from atman.toml, picks the
//   polynomial degree that hits the precision target, emits the
//   coefficient vector at compile time, evaluates as a dot product
//   against [1, x, x², ...] at runtime. No libm call. KART makes
//   this strategy uniform across all univariate continuous
//   functions on bounded domains.
//
// sqrt(x), x ∈ [0, b]
//   Same shape as log. Chebyshev expansion on the bounded domain.
//   For very-wide-domain sqrt the lookup-table tier may win because
//   the Chebyshev polynomial degree balloons — the compiler picks.
//
// exp(x), x ∈ [a, b]
//   Same shape. Chebyshev. The unbounded-domain case (x ∈ ℝ) needs
//   range-reduction (e.g. write x = n*ln2 + r, expand exp(r) only)
//   which is doable as a compile-time transformation but is the
//   non-trivial part.
//
// sin(x), cos(x), tan(x)
//   Same family. Periodic, so range-reduction is mandatory before
//   the polynomial step. CORDIC-style decomposition into sequences
//   of shifts and adds is also viable on hardware-targeted backends.
//
// pow(x, y)
//   Two-argument case. KART says even multivariate continuous
//   functions decompose into compositions of univariates plus
//   addition. pow(x, y) = exp(y * log(x)) is the standard such
//   decomposition; once log and exp are wired, pow is essentially
//   free.


// ==========================================================================
// Section 2 — blocked on intrinsics (pseudo-Sutra what the bodies
// would look like once the approximation pass lands)
// ==========================================================================
//
// function scalar log(scalar x) {
//     // Compile-time: read [math] section, pick Chebyshev degree
//     // and coefficients for log on the inferred bounded domain.
//     // Runtime: dot(coeffs, [1, x, x², ..., x^n]).
//     return _chebyshev_eval(_log_coeffs, x);
// }
//
// (And similarly for the others. The compile-time work is the
// coefficient generator + bounded-domain inference; the runtime is
// just the dot product against the basis evaluations.)


// ==========================================================================
// Section 3 — intrinsic declarations
// ==========================================================================

intrinsic function scalar log(scalar x);
intrinsic function scalar sqrt(scalar x);
intrinsic function scalar exp(scalar x);
intrinsic function scalar sin(scalar x);
intrinsic function scalar cos(scalar x);
intrinsic function scalar tan(scalar x);
intrinsic function scalar pow(scalar x, scalar y);
